      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Environmental Harmony'' (editorial, Jan. 1), you fault the Bush administration for doing nothing to create or enforce a national policy on global warming, including production of fuel-efficient cars.</p>
        <p>Yet the administration may be more in touch with the electorate than not, for little is done on a local level to recognize these realities.</p>
        <p>In my state, billions are devoted to accommodating increased traffic without regard to global warming, fossil-fuel consumption, air pollution, land loss, road deaths, debt to foreign nations or even war to ensure access to oil.</p>
        <p>But whenever there is planning for public transportation, expense is cited as the obstacle.</p>
        <p>David Ray  Tucson, Jan. 1, 2007</p>
      </block>
